chen und Techniken, die weitreichende Netzwerke zu bilden imstande waren. Die Beiträger_innen liefern Antworten auf die Frage, welche Akteure welches Phänomen globalisiert haben.  aGlobal history and actor-network theory are currently among the most discussed theoretical frameworks in the social sciences - however, they have yet to be put together. This volume closes that gap and examines the compatibility of global history views and the perspectives of actor-network theory. The contributions show how the theoretical assumptions and methodical approaches of Bruno Latour, the most prominent advocate of agent-network theory, can contribute to the renewal of global history: no longer asking for a supposedly almighty power called globalization, but for concrete people, things, and techniques which can create extensive networks. This also serves to investigate which actors globalized which phenomenon at which time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aActor-network theoryvCongresses. 0aElectric networksvCongresses. 0aGlobalizationxHistoryvCongresses. 0aWorld historyvCongresses. 4aAkteur-Netzwerk-Theorie. 4aBruno Latour. 4aGeschichtstheorie. 4aGeschichtswissenschaft. 4aGlobalgeschichte. 4aKulturgeschichte. 4aScience and Technology Studies. 4aTechnik. 4aTechnikgeschichte. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  aActor-network-theory.  aBruno Latour.  aCultural History.  aGlobal History.  aHistory of Technology.  aHistory.  aScience and Technology Studies.  aTechnology.  aTheory of History.1 aAbu-Chouka, Sherin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerstenberger, Debora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerstenberger, Debora, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGlasman, Joël, econtributor.4ctb4https